{{Infobox religious biography |background = #FFD068 | color = black |name = Imakita Kōsen |image = |caption = |birth name = |alias = |dharma name = |birth_date = 1816 |birth_place = [[Settsū Province|Settsu, Japan]] |death_date = 16 January 1892 |death_place = |nationality = |religion = [[Zen Buddhism]] |school = [[Rinzai]] |lineage = |title = [[Zen Master]] |location = |education = |occupation = |teacher = |reincarnation of = |predecessor = [[Gisan Zenkai]] |successor = [[Soyen Shaku]] |students = |spouse = |partner = |children = |website = }} {{ZenBuddhism}} {{Japanese name|Imakita}} {{nihongo|'''Imakita Kōsen'''|今北 洪川||3 August 1816 - 16 January 1892}} was a Japanese [[Rinzai]] Zen [[rōshi]] and [[Neo-Confucianism|Neo-Confucianist]].
Kosen did his Zen training under [[Daisetsu Shoen]] (1797–1855) at [[Sōkoku-ji]] and received [[Dharma transmission|inka]] from [[Gisan Zenkai]] at Sōgen-ji in Okayama. Kosen was instrumental in bringing Zen to lay practitioners and to the west. Kosen's [[Dharma heir]] [[Soyen Shaku]]<ref name="Victoria, 37;237">Victoria, 37;237</ref><ref name="Dumoulin, 407">Dumoulin, 407</ref><ref name="Sawada, 214">Sawada, 214</ref> participated in the [[World Parliament of Religions]] in Chicago, which introduced Soyen Shaku's student [[D.T. Suzuki]] to [[Paul Carus]] and western [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|Theosophy]]. Kosen's dharma descendant Tetsuo Sōkatsu established [[Ningen Zen Kyodan]], an independent lay-Rinzai school.<ref name=ningen-home>[http://www.ningen-zen.com/ningen-zen/home.shtml Ningen Zen Home] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316112314/http://www.ningen-zen.com/ningen-zen/home.shtml |date=2013-03-16 }}</ref>
As one-time head abbot of [[Engakuji]] in [[Kamakura, Japan]], he was known as a government loyalist and is remembered for his support of [[Emperor Meiji]]—in the 1870s serving as Doctrinal Instructor for the Ministry of Doctrine.<ref name="Victoria, 37;237"/><ref name="Dumoulin, 407"/><ref name="Sawada, 214"/>
