'''Neuroheuristics''' (or '''Neuristics''') studies the dynamic relations between the complex knowledge acquired by [[neuroscience]] by means of an approach not reducible in an expertise since it is continuously renewed at every stage of progress towards scientific discovery.
==Etymology== The word comes from the Greek νεύρον ([[neuron]], which refers to the nerve cell<ref name="Neuron">{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/410669/neuron|title=Neuron |publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica }}</ref>) and εύρισκω ("euriskein" [[heuristic]], which refers to a [[problem-solving]] procedure that is often characterized by its informal, intuitive and speculative features<ref name="Heuristics">{{cite web |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/593468/thought/275926/Structures-of-problems|title=Structure of problems in thought |publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica }}</ref>).
==Paradigm== Neuroheuristics<ref>{{cite web |title=The Neuro Heuristic paradigm |publisher=Neuroheuristic Research Group | url=http://neuroheuristic.org/nhrg/docs/def/NHparadigm.html}}</ref> defines a [[scientific paradigm]] aimed to develop strategies that can be enabled to understand brain and mind following subsequent problems emerging from [[transdisciplinary studies]] including [[philosophy]], [[psychology]], [[neuroscience]], [[pharmacology]], [[physics]], [[artificial intelligence]], [[engineering]], [[computer science]], [[economics]] and [[mathematics]].
The neuroheuristic paradigm was presented for the first time at the conference ''Entrer dans le XXIe siècle : de l'apoptose à la métamorphose'', held in 1994 at the Centro Stefano Franscini [[Monte Verità]], under the auspice of the XV Videart Festival Locarno.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.davel.vd.ch/qfpdavel/0/D3963.pdf|title=Vers un nouveau paradigme en neurosciences|publisher=Archives cantonales vaudoises, document reference PP 525/806.}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=June 2015}}
The research framework introduced by the neuroheuristic paradigm appears as an essential step for the investigation of the information processing effected by the brain because it is the outcome of [[nature and nurture]], at the crossing of [[top-down and bottom-up design]].
The neurobiologists apply a "bottom-up" research strategy in their studies. This strategy seems to prove necessary and sufficient to understand a brain in its entirety after the impressive achievements in studying the entire nervous system of a simple model organism, such as ''[[Caenorhabditis elegans]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=A database featuring behavioral and structural anatomy of ''Caenorhabditis elegans''|url=http://www.wormatlas.org/hermaphrodite/nervous/Neuroframeset.html}} {{cite web |title=Specification of the nervous system of ''C. elegans''| url=http://www.wormbook.org/chapters/www_specnervsys/specnervsys.html}} {{cite journal |last1=White |first1=J.G. |last2=Southgate |first2=E. |last3=Thomson |first3=J.N. |last4=Brenner |first4=S.|title= The Structure of the Nervous System of the Nematode ''Caenorhabditis elegans'' |journal= Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B |volume=314 |issue=1165 |pages=1–340 |year=1986 |doi=10.1098/rstb.1986.0056 |pmid=22462104}} {{cite news|last=Jabr|first=Ferris|title=The Connectome Debate: Is Mapping the Mind of a Worm Worth It?|url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=c-elegans-connectome|newspaper=Scientific American}}</ref> However it is not wholly viable to actual experimentation considering the impossibility of simultaneously examining all cellular elements of the brain and all variables that affect those elements.
The "top-down" strategy with the assistance of [[black box theory]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Botterill|first1=George|last2=Carruthers|first2=Peter|title=The Philosophy of Psychology|year=1999|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521559157|url=http://www.cambridge.org/catalogue/catalogue.asp?isbn=9780511037986}} {{cite journal|last=Von Hilgers| first=Philipp| title=The History of the Black Box: The Clash of a Thing and its Concept| journal=Cultural Politics| year=2011| volume=7| issue=1| pages=41–58| url=http://culturalpolitics.dukejournals.org/content/7/1/41.abstract}}</ref> appears easier to bring to fulfillment but insufficient and irrelevant in understanding the mechanisms coordinating the local networks of cellular elements.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Burke|first=Robert E.|title=Sir Charles Sherrington's the integrative action of the nervous system: a centenary appreciation|journal=Brain|year=2007|volume=130|issue=4|pages=887–894|doi=10.1093/brain/awm022|pmid=17438014}}</ref> The ''neuroheuristic'' (or ''neuristic'') paradigm offers as a needed and possible distinct approach to the study of brain and mind.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=John G.|last2=Villa|first2=Alessandro E.P.|title=The "Conscious I": A Neuroheuristic Approach to the Mind| year=2001| volume=3| series=Frontiers of Life| pages=349–368| isbn=9780120773404 | url=http://neuroheuristic.org/nhrg/msps/_01cftv.zip }} {{cite journal| last=Villa| first=Alessandro E.P.| title=Neuroheuristics, a new paradigm in neuroscience|journal=Rev Med Suisse Romande| year=2000| volume=120| issue=9| pages=743–748| pmid=11094540 |url=http://neuroheuristic.org/nhrg/msps/_00v1.zip }} {{cite journal|last=Villa|first=Alessandro E.P.|title=Neural Coding in the Neuroheuristic Perspective| year=2008| volume=1| series=Biosemiotics| pages=357–377| doi=10.1007/978-1-4020-6340-4_16}} {{cite journal|last1=Villa|first1=Alessandro E.P.|last2=Missonnier|first2=Pascal|last3=Lintas|first3=Alessandra|title=Neuroheuristics of Decision Making: From Neuronal Activity to EEG |year=2012| volume=28| series=Intelligent Systems Reference Library |pages=159–194| doi=10.1007/978-3-642-24647-0_7 }}</ref> In this framework, a "result" cannot be simply positive or negative because the process itself cannot be reduced to proficiency as such. Dynamics is an essential feature of the neuroheuristic paradigm, but it cannot be merely considered as the neurobiological facet of [[holism]] as opposed to [[reductionism]].
