'''Ordinary and extraordinary care''' are distinguished by some [[bioethics|bioethical]] theories, including the teaching of the [[Catholicism|Catholic Church]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Wildes|first=Kevin J.|title=Ordinary and extraordinary means and the quality of life.|journal=Theological Studies|year=1996|volume=57|url=https://www.questia.com/googleScholar.qst?docId=5000410475|accessdate=20 July 2011}}</ref> Ordinary care is [[Obligation|obligatory]], but can become extraordinary care under certain situations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.all.org/learn/euthanasia/ordinary-vs-extraordinary-care/|title=Ordinary vs. Extraordinary Care - Euthanasia {{!}} American Life League|website=American Life League|access-date=2016-12-04}}</ref>  Extraordinary care is care whose provision involves a disproportionately great burden on the patient or community, and hence is not [[Morality|morally]] obligatory.  

On the Catholic version of the distinction, the natural provision of life necessities, such as food, air, and water, is an example of ordinary care, although it does not exhaust ordinary care, since easily performed [[medical procedure]]s (that do not impose an undue burden on patient and community) will also be ordinary care.

