'''Robert Stern''' (born February 1962)<ref name=DOB>{{cite web|title=Stern, Robert, 1962–...|url=http://viaf.org/viaf/69006005/#Stern,_Robert,_1962-....|publisher=VIAF|accessdate=13 April 2014}}</ref> is a professor of philosophy at the [[University of Sheffield]], [[Sheffield]], United Kingdom. He is a British philosopher who is known for his work on the [[history of philosophy]], particularly [[Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel|Hegel]] and [[Immanuel Kant]]. His current research is focused on the Danish ethicist [[Knud Ejler Løgstrup]].  

==Biography==
Stern graduated from [[St John's College, Cambridge]], and then became a [[research fellow]] there. He has been a professor at the University of Sheffield since 2000, and was the head of the Department of Philosophy from 2004 to 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=Profile: Robert Stern|url=https://www.shef.ac.uk/philosophy/staff/profiles/sternr|publisher=University of Sheffield|accessdate=13 April 2014}}</ref>

He is on the editorial board of the ''[[European Journal of Philosophy]]'',<ref name=European>{{cite web|title=European Board of Philosophy – Editorial Board|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/10.1111/%28ISSN%291468-0378/homepage/EditorialBoard.html|publisher=Wiley|accessdate=13 April 2014}}</ref> and he is the current president of the [[British Philosophical Association]].<ref name=About>{{cite web|title=About us|url=http://www.bpa.ac.uk/about|publisher=British Philosophical Association|accessdate=13 April 2014}}</ref>

